    <dlgPart>
      <portrait>Esbenus</portrait>
      <speaker_name />
      <npc_text>"They say that raiders fuck up once. One mistake and you're dead.

"The group that took me in made a mistake falling for a 'fake retreat' trick. I saw it coming and tried to warn them, but in the heat of the battle, nobody listened to me. I didn't stick around and left while I still could.

"My next group fared better, until a desert storm forced us to seek shelter. We saw a mountain up ahead and pressed on, despite being blinded by the storm. When we had reached the mountain, we could see that it wasn't what we had expected. There was a temple carved into its façade with a small entrance to what appeared to be a cave. It was a strange place and now, I doubt it was a cave at all. My men tried to warn me – no, the irony isn't lost on me, but I dismissed their warnings as tribal superstitions and paid dearly for it. Only a handful of us got out alive.

"And so I went from one group to another, until I had had enough of the wasteland and decided to move south in search of greener pastures."</npc_text>
      <onLoadScripts />
      <answers>
        <dlgAnsw>
          <text>"What happened in that cave?"</text>
          <def_link>101</def_link>
          <checkOnAppear />
          <checksOnClick />
          <linksOnClick />
          <scriptsOnClick />
        </dlgAnsw>
      </answers>
      <UID>100</UID>
    </dlgPart>
    <dlgPart>
      <portrait>Esbenus</portrait>
      <speaker_name />
      <npc_text>"It reeked of death. Skulls and bones everywhere... My men begged me to leave, told me that they'd heard stories about this place. Bad stories. Still, the storm outside was real, the stories ... well, stories. People tell them for different reasons – to amuse, to scare, or to keep other people away.

"It got me thinking. The "cave" was small. The walls were rough, but seemingly man-made. You didn't have to be smart to know that there was more to it than that one small chamber. I told my men that these walls must hold great treasure – that was enough for them to abandon their caution and start looking."</npc_text>
      <onLoadScripts />
      <answers>
        <dlgAnsw>
          <text>Continue.</text>
          <def_link>102</def_link>
          <checkOnAppear />
          <checksOnClick />
          <linksOnClick />
          <scriptsOnClick />
        </dlgAnsw>
      </answers>
      <UID>101</UID>
    </dlgPart>
    <dlgPart>
      <portrait>Esbenus</portrait>
      <speaker_name />
      <npc_text>"After hours of searching, we had stumbled upon a switch. It opened a hidden passage leading to another two chambers. The first one contained two strange objects – each one as tall as a man. They were indistinguishable – carbon copies of each other, just sitting there untouched. You could mistake them for some idols, if not for the metal pipes that disappeared into the floor. There were no clues as to their purpose or the reason why someone needed two of them.

"The second chamber had metal pipes running along the walls and was empty, save for a single platform. It was like a metal cart with railings. I remember wondering who would possibly waste so much metal to build such a contraption. Then, Nicanor stepped onto it and the platform went down – all the way through the floor and into the very depths of the underworld, judging by the noise and red glow.

"Soon, the platform returned. Without him."</npc_text>
      <onLoadScripts />
      <answers>
        <dlgAnsw>
          <text>Continue.</text>
          <def_link>103</def_link>
          <checkOnAppear />
          <checksOnClick />
          <linksOnClick />
          <scriptsOnClick />
        </dlgAnsw>
      </answers>
      <UID>102</UID>
    </dlgPart>
    <dlgPart>
      <portrait>Esbenus</portrait>
      <speaker_name />
      <npc_text>"I told this story many times and each time I wonder why I didn't immediately take my men and flee. It seems so obvious now, but back then, in that chamber, we felt like we had stepped into a fairy tale. It was a tale rife with disappearing walls, strange idols, and magic carts taking only the worthy to hidden treasures beyond their wildest dreams. I sent my best men to see what was down there and bring back Nicanor. None of them returned.

"When the platform came back, it was as if it had come back for us. We ran outside to clear our minds and to escape from the hidden evils of that place."</npc_text>
      <onLoadScripts>
        <string>aod.npc_esbenus_talkedAboutHellgate = true;</string>
      </onLoadScripts>
      <answers>
        <dlgAnsw>
